window.MODULES=window.MODULES||{};window.MODULES["echocardiography"]={"slug": "echocardiography", "title": "Echocardiography: A Practical Reading Module", "tagline": "From systematic report sequence to fellowship-level quantification — read the study, not just the numbers.", "level": 2, "readMin": 58, "sections": [{"id": "how-to-read", "title": "How to Read a Study: The Systematic Sequence", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The single most common mistake residents make is reading an echo the way they read the report — jumping to the impression. Read every study the same way, every time, in the same order. A fixed sequence means you never forget the pericardium on the tamponade patient or the RV on the PE patient. The habit is the skill."}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The workflow below mirrors the American Society of Echocardiography (ASE) chamber-quantification and reporting standards. First characterize the images, then the chambers, then the valves, then the pericardium and great vessels, and only then synthesize. Confirm every abnormal finding in at least two views before you believe it."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "The universal reading order", "items": ["<strong>Technical quality and rhythm.</strong> Is this a good study or a foreshortened, poorly windowed one? What is the rhythm on the strip? Off-axis apical views inflate EF and hide apical thrombus.", "<strong>LV — size, wall thickness, systolic function (EF), regional wall motion, GLS.</strong> Biplane Simpson EF is the quantitative standard; eyeball only to sanity-check.", "<strong>Diastolic function and filling pressures.</strong> Run the full ASE algorithm rather than reporting a single E/A.", "<strong>RV — size, function (TAPSE, S prime, FAC), and estimated systolic pressure (RVSP from TR jet).</strong>", "<strong>LA and RA volumes.</strong> LA volume index is the structural memory of chronic diastolic dysfunction.", "<strong>Valves — morphology first, then quantitative severity by the correct method for each lesion.</strong>", "<strong>Pericardium, effusion, tamponade physiology.</strong>", "<strong>Aorta, IVC, septa (ASD/PFO/VSD), and any masses or thrombus.</strong>", "<strong>Synthesize into a single hemodynamic story</strong> that a treating clinician can act on."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — reading order \"I've Learned Data From Reading Lots of Valves, Pericardium, And Septa\":</strong> Images/rhythm, LV, Diastole, RV, LA/RA, Valves, Pericardium, Aorta/IVC, Septa. Same order, every study."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Every number on a report is only as good as its angle of insonation. Doppler underestimates velocity by cos(θ); at 20° off-axis the error is about 6%, tolerable, but Doppler done at 30-45° (as often happens when chasing an eccentric MR or AS jet) can meaningfully underestimate gradients. When the number does not fit the picture, suspect the angle before you rewrite the physiology."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Never accept a normal EF as reassurance in a symptomatic patient without checking GLS, diastology, RV function, and valves. HFpEF, high-output states, constrictive physiology, amyloid, and severe MR/AS all coexist with a \"normal\" ejection fraction."}]}, {"id": "lv-quant", "title": "LV Quantification: EF, Volumes, and Geometry", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Left ventricular ejection fraction remains the number that drives device eligibility, heart-failure classification, and chemotherapy decisions, so it must be measured, not guessed. The reference method is the biplane method of disks (modified Simpson): trace the endocardial border in the apical 4- and 2-chamber views at end-diastole and end-systole, and the software integrates stacked disks to give volumes and EF."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "Core LV parameters and normal ranges (ASE)", "entries": [{"term": "LVEF (biplane Simpson)", "def": "Normal ≥52% (men), ≥54% (women) by ASE chamber-quantification cut points. Clinically, the 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA heart-failure classification uses EF ≤40% (HFrEF), 41-49% (HFmrEF), and ≥50% (HFpEF)."}, {"term": "LV end-diastolic diameter (LVEDD)", "def": "Normal ~42-58 mm (men), 38-52 mm (women). Linear measure at the basal level in parasternal long axis."}, {"term": "LV end-diastolic volume index", "def": "Normal ≤74 mL/m² (men), ≤61 mL/m² (women). Volumes are more reliable than linear diameters when geometry is distorted."}, {"term": "Septal/posterior wall thickness", "def": "Normal ≤10 mm (women) / ≤11 mm (men). >15 mm suggests significant hypertrophy; asymmetric septal thickening raises HCM."}, {"term": "LV mass index", "def": "Normal ≤95 g/m² (women), ≤115 g/m² (men). Used with relative wall thickness to classify concentric vs eccentric remodeling."}]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "When endocardial borders are poorly defined — a common problem — use an ultrasound-enhancing agent (contrast). Contrast-enhanced LVEF correlates far better with cardiac MRI than a poorly bordered non-contrast trace, and it is the standard of care whenever two or more contiguous segments are not well seen. 3D echo EF, when available, avoids the geometric assumptions of biplane Simpson and is closer to the MRI reference."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "EF estimation methods, ranked", "head": ["Method", "How", "Reliability", "When to use"], "rows": [["Biplane Simpson (MOD)", "Trace endocardium in A4C + A2C", "Reference clinical standard", "Every routine study"], ["3D volumetric EF", "Full-volume acquisition, semi-automated", "Best, near-CMR; no geometric assumption", "Good windows, device decisions, serial oncology"], ["Contrast (UEA) Simpson", "Opacify LV cavity, then trace", "Rescues poor windows", "≥2 contiguous segments not seen"], ["Teichholz (linear)", "Cube formula from one diameter", "Obsolete for EF; do not use", "Never for regional disease — assumes symmetry"], ["Visual eyeball", "Gestalt", "Operator-dependent", "Sanity check only, not the report number"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Do not report EF by the Teichholz linear method in any patient with regional wall-motion abnormality, prior MI, or aneurysm. Extrapolating global EF from a single basal diameter assumes uniform contraction the ischemic ventricle does not have."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Foreshortening is the enemy of accurate volumes. If the apex looks rounded and the LV looks short, you are cutting across the true apex and will overestimate EF while missing an apical aneurysm or thrombus. Acquire the longest LV you can find, keep the mitral annulus and apex in the same plane, and use contrast when in doubt."}]}, {"id": "gls", "title": "Global Longitudinal Strain and the Bullseye", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Strain imaging measures myocardial deformation — the percentage a segment shortens — rather than endocardial excursion. Global longitudinal strain (GLS) is derived by speckle-tracking across the three apical views and displayed as a 17-segment polar map, the bullseye. Because strain is a negative number (myocardium shortens), \"more negative\" is better and \"less negative\" is worse. Normal GLS is roughly −20% (more negative than about −18% to −20% is normal); the magnitude, not the sign, is what matters."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "Reading the bullseye", "entries": [{"term": "Color convention", "def": "Red/pink = normal (strongly negative deformation); pink-to-blue = progressively worse; blue = akinetic/absent deformation. The map is arranged apex-center, base-periphery, in the standard coronary distribution."}, {"term": "Normal GLS", "def": "Approximately −20% (values more negative than about −18% considered normal; vendor-dependent). Report the absolute number and the vendor."}, {"term": "Subclinical dysfunction", "def": "GLS worse than about −16% with preserved EF signals early myocardial disease before EF falls."}, {"term": "Coronary territory pattern", "def": "Regional blue segments in a single coronary distribution (e.g., LAD apex/anterior/septum) point to ischemic or infarcted myocardium."}]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "GLS bullseye patterns and their diagnoses", "head": ["Pattern", "Bullseye appearance", "Points toward"], "rows": [["Apical sparing (\"cherry on top\")", "Blue/impaired base and mid, red preserved apex", "Cardiac amyloidosis — high specificity"], ["Regional territorial defect", "Blue in one coronary distribution", "Ischemia / prior MI (LAD, RCA, LCx)"], ["Basal-predominant impairment", "Worse deformation basally", "Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, some infiltrative disease"], ["Diffuse global reduction", "Uniformly less-negative whole map", "Cardiotoxicity, dilated CMP, diffuse process"], ["Preserved EF but reduced GLS", "Global mild worsening", "Subclinical dysfunction — earliest cardiotox signal"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Apical sparing is the amyloid signature.</strong> Relative regional strain ratio (average apical strain ÷ [average basal + mid strain]) >1.0 is highly specific for cardiac amyloidosis. On the bullseye it is the classic red apex sitting inside a blue base — the \"cherry on top.\" Pair it with increased wall thickness, low voltage on ECG, and a granular sparkling myocardium."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "In cardio-oncology, a relative decline in GLS of more than 15% from the patient's own baseline predicts subsequent cancer-therapy-related cardiac dysfunction before EF drops, and prompts cardioprotection (ACEi/ARB plus beta-blocker) per current cardio-oncology consensus. Always compare to the patient's own baseline strain and hold the vendor and machine constant — GLS is not portable across vendors."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Example bullseye maps showing apical sparing in amyloid versus territorial ischemic patterns are catalogued on Radiopaedia.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia — strain / bullseye examples"}]}, {"id": "diastole", "title": "Diastolic Function: The Full ASE Algorithm", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Diastolic assessment estimates LV filling pressure, and it is where residents most often stop at a single E/A ratio. The 2016 ASE/EACVI algorithm integrates four variables and is applied differently depending on whether EF is normal or reduced. Learn the four numbers and their cutoffs cold; they recur on every board exam and every real study."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "The four ASE variables and their abnormal cutoffs", "entries": [{"term": "Septal e′ and lateral e′ (tissue Doppler)", "def": "Abnormal if septal e′ <7 cm/s or lateral e′ <10 cm/s. Reflects intrinsic myocardial relaxation."}, {"term": "E/e′ ratio (average)", "def": "Abnormal if average E/e′ >14 (or septal E/e′ >15, lateral E/e′ >13). Surrogate for elevated LV filling pressure."}, {"term": "LA volume index (LAVi)", "def": "Abnormal if >34 mL/m². The structural memory of chronically elevated filling pressure."}, {"term": "Peak TR velocity", "def": "Abnormal if >2.8 m/s. Surrogate for pulmonary pressure elevation driven by left-heart filling."}]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "Algorithm when EF is NORMAL (assessing whether diastolic function is abnormal)", "items": ["Assess the four variables: average E/e′ >14, septal e′ <7 / lateral e′ <10, TR velocity >2.8 m/s, LAVi >34 mL/m².", "If <2 of 4 are positive → normal diastolic function.", "If 2 of 4 are positive → indeterminate.", "If >2 of 4 (i.e., 3-4) are positive → diastolic dysfunction with elevated filling pressures."]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Algorithm when EF is REDUCED, or myocardial disease with normal EF (grading + estimating filling pressure)", "items": ["Start with mitral inflow E/A ratio and E velocity.", "E/A ≤0.8 with E ≤50 cm/s → Grade I (impaired relaxation), normal LA pressure.", "E/A ≥2 → Grade III (restrictive filling), elevated LA pressure.", "E/A ≤0.8 with E >50 cm/s, OR E/A between 0.8 and 2 → apply three tiebreakers: average E/e′ >14, TR velocity >2.8 m/s, LAVi >34 mL/m².", "Two or three tiebreakers positive → Grade II, elevated LA pressure. Two or three negative → Grade I, normal LA pressure. One positive/one negative → indeterminate."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Diastolic dysfunction grades", "head": ["Grade", "Pattern", "E/A", "LA pressure", "Clinical correlate"], "rows": [["Grade I", "Impaired relaxation", "≤0.8", "Normal", "Aging, LVH, early disease; often asymptomatic"], ["Grade II", "Pseudonormal", "0.8-2 (tiebreakers +)", "Elevated", "Symptomatic HFpEF/HFrEF; the trap that mimics normal"], ["Grade III", "Restrictive", "≥2", "Markedly elevated", "Advanced HF, amyloid, constrictive/restrictive disease"]]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 2, "text": "Several ancillary signs support the algorithm when the four core variables are borderline. Pulmonary vein flow shifting to diastolic dominance (blunted S/D ratio <1) and a pulmonary-vein atrial-reversal (Ar) duration exceeding the mitral A-wave duration by more than 30 ms both indicate elevated LV end-diastolic pressure. A mid-diastolic L-wave suggests markedly delayed relaxation with high filling pressure. When resting numbers are indeterminate but the patient is dyspneic on exertion, diastolic stress (exercise) echocardiography can unmask elevated pressures — an average E/e′ that rises above 14 with a TR velocity above 2.8 m/s at peak stress supports HFpEF."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic for the four ASE variables — \"LATE\":</strong> <strong>L</strong>A volume index (>34), <strong>A</strong>verage E/e′ (>14), <strong>T</strong>R velocity (>2.8), <strong>e</strong>′ velocity (septal <7 / lateral <10). It is \"LATE\" in the disease when these turn positive."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "The 2016 algorithm is invalid in several settings: atrial fibrillation (no organized A wave, beat-to-beat variability), significant mitral valve disease or mitral annular calcification, mitral prosthesis, ≥moderate MR, LBBB/paced rhythm, and severe annular calcification. In these, e′ and E/e′ mislead — use LAVi, TR velocity, pulmonary vein flow, and clinical context instead."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Pseudonormalization (Grade II) is the concept that separates a resident from a fellow: as filling pressure rises, the E/A ratio passes through a \"normal\" 0.8-2 window on its way from impaired relaxation to restriction. A normal-looking mitral inflow in a dyspneic patient is a red flag, not reassurance. Confirm with e′ (which stays low once myocardial relaxation is impaired and does not pseudonormalize) and the Valsalva maneuver, which unmasks the underlying impaired-relaxation pattern by dropping preload."}]}, {"id": "rv", "title": "Right Ventricle: Size, Function, and Pressure", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The RV is the chamber most often ignored and most often diagnostic — in pulmonary embolism, pulmonary hypertension, RV infarction, and advanced left-heart failure. Its crescentic geometry defeats the volumetric assumptions used for the LV, so RV function is assessed with a panel of surrogate measures rather than a single EF."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "RV function parameters and abnormal cutoffs (ASE)", "entries": [{"term": "TAPSE", "def": "Tricuspid annular plane systolic excursion by M-mode of the lateral annulus. Abnormal <17 mm. Simple, reproducible, load-dependent measure of longitudinal RV function."}, {"term": "RV S′ (tissue Doppler)", "def": "Systolic velocity of the lateral tricuspid annulus. Abnormal <9.5 cm/s. Complements TAPSE."}, {"term": "Fractional area change (FAC)", "def": "(EDA − ESA)/EDA in the RV-focused A4C. Abnormal <35%. Reflects both longitudinal and radial function."}, {"term": "RV basal diameter", "def": "Abnormal >41 mm at the base in the RV-focused apical view. RV:LV basal diameter ratio >1.0 signals significant dilation."}, {"term": "RV free-wall strain", "def": "Abnormal if less negative than about −20% (i.e., magnitude <20%). Sensitive early marker of RV dysfunction."}]}, {"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "RV systolic pressure (RVSP), which equals pulmonary artery systolic pressure in the absence of RVOT obstruction or pulmonic stenosis, is estimated from the tricuspid regurgitation jet using the simplified Bernoulli equation. Measure the peak TR velocity, convert to a gradient, and add an estimate of right atrial pressure from the IVC. A shortened pulmonary artery acceleration time (<105 ms), a mid-systolic notch in the RVOT Doppler envelope, and a dilated main pulmonary artery are supportive signs of pulmonary hypertension."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "Estimating RVSP (= PASP) from the TR jet", "items": ["Measure peak TR jet velocity (V, in m/s) with continuous-wave Doppler, aligning parallel to the jet across multiple views.", "Apply simplified Bernoulli: peak RV-to-RA gradient = 4V².", "Estimate right atrial pressure (RAP) from IVC size and collapse.", "RVSP = 4V² + RAP. Example: TR velocity 3.5 m/s → 4(3.5²) = 49 mmHg; add RAP 8 → RVSP ≈ 57 mmHg."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Estimating RA pressure from the IVC", "head": ["IVC diameter", "Inspiratory collapse", "Estimated RAP"], "rows": [["≤2.1 cm", ">50% collapse", "3 mmHg (normal, range 0-5)"], ["≤2.1 cm", "<50% collapse", "8 mmHg (intermediate)"], [">2.1 cm", ">50% collapse", "8 mmHg (intermediate)"], [">2.1 cm", "<50% collapse", "15 mmHg (high)"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>McConnell sign</strong> — akinesia of the RV mid free wall with preserved apical contraction — is relatively specific for acute pulmonary embolism (acute pressure overload), distinguishing it from chronic pulmonary hypertension where the whole free wall is impaired. Pair with a dilated RV, septal flattening (D-shaped LV), and a TR velocity that is only modestly elevated because the thin acute RV cannot generate high pressures — the \"60/60 sign\" (TR gradient <60 mmHg with pulmonary acceleration time <60 ms)."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "A \"normal\" TR velocity does not exclude severe RV failure. A failing RV may be unable to generate a high pressure, so the estimated RVSP can look deceptively mild while the RV is dilated and hypokinetic. Read RV size and function alongside pressure — never pressure alone."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Septal position tells you the loading state at a glance. Systolic septal flattening (D-shaped LV in the short axis at end-systole) indicates RV <em>pressure</em> overload; diastolic flattening indicates RV <em>volume</em> overload (e.g., ASD, severe TR). Both present together in advanced pulmonary hypertension. The eccentricity index quantifies it."}]}, {"id": "aortic-stenosis", "title": "Valvular Quantification I — Aortic Stenosis by Continuity", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Aortic stenosis severity rests on three numbers: peak jet velocity, mean gradient, and aortic valve area (AVA). AVA is derived from the continuity equation, which applies conservation of flow — what passes through the LV outflow tract must pass through the valve. Getting AS right is the highest-yield valve skill because it drives the timing of AVR/TAVR."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "The continuity equation for AVA", "items": ["Measure LVOT diameter (D) in the parasternal long axis at mid-systole; compute LVOT area = 0.785 × D² (πr²).", "Measure LVOT velocity-time integral (VTI) with pulsed-wave Doppler just proximal to the valve (A5C or A3C).", "Measure aortic jet VTI with continuous-wave Doppler across the valve, using multiple windows (apical, right parasternal, suprasternal) to capture the highest velocity.", "AVA = (LVOT area × LVOT VTI) ÷ AV VTI. Flow in = flow out.", "Sanity-check with the dimensionless index (DVI) = LVOT VTI ÷ AV VTI; <0.25 indicates severe AS and is independent of LVOT measurement error."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Aortic stenosis severity (ACC/AHA / ASE)", "head": ["Parameter", "Sclerosis/Mild", "Moderate", "Severe"], "rows": [["Peak velocity (m/s)", "<3.0", "3.0-4.0", "≥4.0"], ["Mean gradient (mmHg)", "<20", "20-40", "≥40"], ["AVA (cm²)", ">1.5", "1.0-1.5", "<1.0"], ["Indexed AVA (cm²/m²)", ">0.85", "0.6-0.85", "<0.6"], ["Dimensionless index", ">0.50", "0.25-0.50", "<0.25"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "The most common continuity-equation error is the LVOT diameter — because it is squared, a 10% measurement error becomes roughly a 20% error in area. Measure D in mid-systole, inner-edge to inner-edge, immediately adjacent to the valve, and zoom in. If AVA and gradients disagree, re-measure the LVOT before you re-classify the patient."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 2, "label": "Low-gradient severe AS — the fellowship trap", "entries": [{"term": "Classical low-flow, low-gradient (LFLG)", "def": "AVA <1.0 cm² but mean gradient <40 mmHg because EF is reduced (<50%) and stroke volume is low. Use dobutamine stress echo to distinguish truly severe AS (AVA stays <1.0, gradient rises) from pseudo-severe (AVA opens up with increased flow)."}, {"term": "Paradoxical low-flow, low-gradient", "def": "AVA <1.0 cm² with low gradient despite preserved EF, driven by a small, hypertrophied LV with low stroke volume index (<35 mL/m²). Confirm severity with valve calcium scoring by CT (Agatston)."}, {"term": "Normal-flow, low-gradient", "def": "Often measurement error or truly moderate AS. Re-check the LVOT and the alignment of the CW jet."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Dobutamine stress echo in classical LFLG AS also assesses <em>contractile/flow reserve</em> (≥20% rise in stroke volume). Absence of flow reserve identifies a higher-risk surgical group and often argues for a transcatheter approach. When echo remains ambiguous, aortic valve calcium score by CT (severe likely: >2000 AU men, >1200 AU women) adjudicates."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Continuous-wave Doppler AS jet envelopes and calcified valve morphology are illustrated on Radiopaedia.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia — aortic stenosis imaging"}]}, {"id": "mitral-pisa", "title": "Valvular Quantification II — Regurgitation by PISA", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Regurgitant lesion severity is best quantified, not eyeballed from color-flow area alone. The proximal isovelocity surface area (PISA) method quantifies the effective regurgitant orifice area (EROA) and regurgitant volume by exploiting the hemispheric flow-convergence zone that forms proximal to a regurgitant orifice. It applies to mitral regurgitation most commonly, and to tricuspid and aortic regurgitation with modification."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "PISA method for mitral regurgitation", "items": ["Zoom on the regurgitant orifice and shift the color Nyquist baseline down (toward the direction of the jet) to ~30-40 cm/s so the flow-convergence hemisphere is well seen.", "Measure the PISA radius (r) from the orifice to the first aliasing hemisphere at peak systole.", "Flow rate = 2πr² × aliasing velocity (Va).", "EROA = flow rate ÷ peak MR jet velocity (CW). Regurgitant volume = EROA × MR VTI.", "Interpret against severity thresholds."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Mitral regurgitation severity (primary MR, ACC/AHA)", "head": ["Parameter", "Mild", "Moderate", "Severe"], "rows": [["EROA (cm²)", "<0.20", "0.20-0.39", "≥0.40"], ["Regurgitant volume (mL)", "<30", "30-59", "≥60"], ["Regurgitant fraction (%)", "<30", "30-49", "≥50"], ["Vena contracta width (cm)", "<0.3", "0.3-0.69", "≥0.7"], ["Jet / supportive", "Small central", "Variable", "Large, wall-impinging (Coanda); systolic pulmonary vein flow reversal"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Systolic flow reversal in the pulmonary veins</strong> is a specific sign of severe MR — the regurgitant volume is so large it backs up into the pulmonary veins during systole. A dense, triangular, early-peaking CW MR jet (rather than a rounded parabola) also signals severe MR with rapid LA pressure equalization."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Do not apply the severe primary-MR thresholds unchanged to secondary (functional) MR, and do not grade MR from color jet area alone — eccentric wall-hugging (Coanda) jets look small on color but can be severe, while central jets that entrain LA blood look large but may be moderate. Always integrate PISA, vena contracta, and pulmonary vein flow."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "PISA assumes a single, circular, hemispheric orifice and is least reliable with multiple jets, non-circular orifices (typical of secondary MR), and eccentric jets — precisely the cases where it matters most. Three-dimensional vena contracta area and 3D-derived EROA overcome the geometric assumption. For tricuspid regurgitation the same physics apply but the aliasing velocity is set differently and severity thresholds are distinct (severe TR: EROA ≥0.40 cm², VC ≥0.7 cm, dense CW jet, hepatic vein systolic reversal)."}]}, {"id": "mitral-stenosis-pht", "title": "Valvular Quantification III — Mitral Stenosis by PHT", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Mitral stenosis severity is anchored on the mitral valve area (MVA). The pressure half-time (PHT) method estimates MVA from the rate of decay of the diastolic transmitral gradient — the tighter the valve, the slower the LA empties and the longer the pressure half-time. Planimetry of the valve orifice in the parasternal short axis is the complementary anatomic gold standard."}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 1, "label": "Pressure half-time method", "items": ["Record the transmitral diastolic inflow with continuous-wave Doppler.", "Measure the pressure half-time — the time for the peak gradient to fall to half its value (equivalently, for peak velocity to fall by a factor of √2).", "MVA = 220 ÷ PHT (empiric constant).", "Cross-check with 2D/3D planimetry of the orifice in the parasternal short axis, and with the mean transmitral gradient."]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Mitral stenosis severity (ACC/AHA / ASE)", "head": ["Parameter", "Progressive (mild-mod)", "Severe", "Very severe"], "rows": [["MVA (cm²)", ">1.5", "≤1.5", "≤1.0"], ["Pressure half-time (ms)", "<150", "≥150", "≥220"], ["Mean gradient (mmHg)", "<5-10 (rate-dependent)", "often >5-10", "high"], ["PASP (mmHg)", "<30", "30-50", ">50"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "The pressure half-time method is invalidated by significant aortic regurgitation (the AR jet raises LV diastolic pressure and shortens PHT, overestimating MVA), by tachycardia and atrial fibrillation (fusion of E and A), and immediately after balloon valvuloplasty when LA/LV compliance is changing acutely. In these settings, trust planimetry and mean gradient over PHT."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "The mean transmitral gradient is heart-rate dependent — it rises with tachycardia because diastole shortens. A patient in sinus at rest may have a \"non-severe\" gradient that becomes severe with exercise or AF with rapid ventricular response. Report the heart rate alongside the gradient, and consider exercise echo when symptoms outstrip resting numbers."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The Wilkins score (leaflet mobility, thickening, calcification, subvalvular disease; each 1-4, total 16) predicts suitability for percutaneous mitral balloon valvuloplasty — a score ≤8 favors an excellent result, while heavy calcification, significant subvalvular disease, or ≥moderate MR argue against it. Rheumatic disease remains the dominant etiology worldwide; look for the classic doming \"hockey-stick\" anterior leaflet."}]}, {"id": "shunts", "title": "Shunts: ASD, PFO, VSD, and Qp/Qs", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Intracardiac shunts are quantified by their hemodynamic burden — the ratio of pulmonary to systemic flow (Qp/Qs) — and localized with color Doppler, agitated-saline contrast, and transesophageal echo. The direction and timing of flow, plus the response of the right heart, tell the story."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "Shunt lesions", "entries": [{"term": "Secundum ASD", "def": "Most common ASD; defect in the fossa ovalis. Left-to-right shunt causes RA/RV volume overload, RV dilation, and diastolic septal flattening. Best seen in subcostal views; color shows flow across the septum."}, {"term": "Patent foramen ovale (PFO)", "def": "Flap-valve interatrial communication present in ~25% of adults. Usually no resting shunt; right-to-left shunting occurs with Valsalva/cough. Associated with cryptogenic stroke and platypnea-orthodeoxia."}, {"term": "Ventricular septal defect (VSD)", "def": "High-velocity left-to-right systolic jet (LV pressure >> RV). A small restrictive VSD is loud and high-gradient; a large non-restrictive VSD equalizes pressures and can reverse (Eisenmenger)."}, {"term": "Sinus venosus / primum ASD", "def": "Sinus venosus defects (near SVC/RUPV) are easily missed on TTE and often need TEE; primum defects are part of AV canal defects and associate with a cleft mitral valve."}]}, {"type": "steps", "depth": 2, "label": "Agitated saline (bubble) study for shunt detection", "items": ["Agitate saline with a small air/blood mix between two syringes and inject into a peripheral vein during imaging of the RA.", "Opacify the right atrium fully, then watch the left atrium for 3-5 cardiac cycles.", "Bubbles in the LA within ≤3 beats → intracardiac shunt (PFO/ASD). Appearance after >3-5 beats → suspect intrapulmonary shunt (e.g., pulmonary AVM, hepatopulmonary syndrome).", "Repeat with Valsalva release to transiently raise RA pressure and provoke right-to-left flow."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Timing separates the shunt:</strong> early bubbles (≤3 beats) = intracardiac; late bubbles (>3-5 beats) = intrapulmonary. A hemodynamically significant left-to-right shunt is generally taken as Qp/Qs >1.5, which supports closure of an ASD in the presence of RV volume overload."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Before closing an ASD, exclude significant pulmonary vascular disease — closing a defect that has become a pop-off valve for a high-resistance pulmonary circuit (Eisenmenger physiology, right-to-left or bidirectional shunt) is harmful. Assess pulmonary pressures, shunt direction, and pulmonary vascular resistance; resting right-to-left shunting and severe pulmonary hypertension are contraindications to closure."}]}, {"id": "pericardium-tamponade", "title": "Pericardial Disease: Effusion, Tamponade, Constriction", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Tamponade is a clinical and hemodynamic diagnosis, not merely the presence of a large effusion — a small effusion that accumulates rapidly can tamponade, while a large chronic one may not. Echo provides the supporting physiology: chamber collapse, exaggerated respiratory variation in inflow, and a plethoric IVC."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "Echo signs of tamponade physiology", "entries": [{"term": "RA systolic collapse", "def": "Inversion of the right atrial free wall during systole; sensitive, and specific when it lasts more than one-third of the cardiac cycle."}, {"term": "RV diastolic collapse", "def": "Inward buckling of the RV free wall in early diastole; highly specific for tamponade. The RV is the low-pressure chamber that yields first to pericardial pressure."}, {"term": "Respirophasic inflow variation", "def": "Mitral inflow E-wave falls >30% (some use >25%) with inspiration; tricuspid inflow rises >60% with inspiration — the echocardiographic pulsus paradoxus from enhanced ventricular interdependence."}, {"term": "IVC plethora", "def": "Dilated IVC (>2.1 cm) with <50% inspiratory collapse — elevated right atrial pressure. Its absence argues against tamponade (in a euvolemic patient)."}, {"term": "Swinging heart", "def": "The heart swinging within a large effusion, the substrate for electrical alternans on ECG."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 1, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — tamponade \"the RIGHT heart gives first\":</strong> <strong>R</strong>A systolic collapse, <strong>I</strong>VC plethora, <strong>G</strong>reater than 30% mitral inflow drop, <strong>H</strong>eart swinging, <strong>T</strong>ricuspid inflow rises / RV diastolic collapse. The thin-walled right chambers collapse before the left."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "Constrictive pericarditis vs restrictive cardiomyopathy", "head": ["Feature", "Constriction", "Restriction"], "rows": [["Septal bounce / shift", "Present (ventricular interdependence)", "Absent"], ["Respirophasic mitral E variation", ">25%", "<10% (minimal)"], ["Medial (septal) e′ (\"annulus paradoxus\")", "Preserved/high, ≥8 cm/s; medial > lateral (\"annulus reversus\")", "Reduced (low e′)"], ["Hepatic vein flow", "Expiratory diastolic flow reversal", "Inspiratory reversal"], ["Pericardium", "Thickened/calcified (CT/MRI)", "Normal"], ["BNP", "Often lower", "Typically higher"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "<strong>Annulus paradoxus and annulus reversus</strong> are the fellowship pearls of constriction. In constriction the tethered pericardium spares (even augments) longitudinal myocardial motion, so medial e′ is <em>preserved or increased</em> — and E/e′ paradoxically falls as filling pressure rises (annulus paradoxus). Because lateral tethering is greatest, medial e′ exceeds lateral e′ (annulus reversus) — the reverse of normal. Combined with a septal bounce, >25% respirophasic E variation, and expiratory hepatic-vein diastolic reversal, these distinguish operable constriction from restriction."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Do not delay pericardiocentesis for a patient in clinical tamponade to gather every echo sign. Echo confirms and guides, but hemodynamic collapse with a pericardial effusion is treated, not further imaged. Conversely, in a hemodynamically stable patient with a large effusion, chamber collapse signs warrant urgent, not emergent, drainage."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Electrical alternans and the imaging of large pericardial effusions are catalogued on Radiopaedia; the classic ECG of a swinging heart is on LITFL.", "url": "https://litfl.com/ecg-library/", "label": "LITFL — electrical alternans ECG"}]}, {"id": "scenarios", "title": "Clinical Scenarios: Putting It Together", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "The report exists to answer a clinical question. These scenarios show how the systematic sequence converges on a diagnosis and a decision."}, {"type": "defs", "depth": 1, "label": "Scenario-to-finding map", "entries": [{"term": "Acute dyspnea, suspected PE", "def": "Look for RV dilation (RV:LV >1), septal flattening (D-shaped LV), McConnell sign (regional mid-free-wall akinesia with spared apex), 60/60 sign, and a mobile RA/RV thrombus-in-transit. A normal RV lowers but does not exclude PE."}, {"term": "HFpEF workup", "def": "Normal EF, reduced GLS, LAVi >34, average E/e′ >14, TR velocity >2.8, concentric LVH. Run the full diastolic algorithm and consider diastolic (exercise) stress echo when resting numbers are indeterminate."}, {"term": "Infiltrative cardiomyopathy / amyloid", "def": "Increased wall thickness with low ECG voltage, granular sparkling myocardium, biatrial enlargement, small pericardial effusion, restrictive filling, and apical-sparing GLS (\"cherry on top\"). Confirm with bone-avid (PYP/DPD) scintigraphy for ATTR or biopsy/serum free light chains for AL."}, {"term": "New systolic murmur post-MI", "def": "Distinguish acute severe MR (papillary muscle rupture — flail leaflet, torrential eccentric jet, flash pulmonary edema) from a post-infarct VSD (left-to-right systolic jet with an oxygen step-up) — both are surgical emergencies."}, {"term": "Embolic stroke, source hunt", "def": "TTE with agitated saline for PFO/ASD; TEE for LA appendage thrombus, aortic atheroma, and valvular vegetations. In AF, the LAA is the key structure."}, {"term": "Endocarditis", "def": "Oscillating vegetation on a valve/device, new regurgitation, abscess (perivalvular echolucency), and dehiscence of a prosthesis. TEE is far more sensitive than TTE, especially for prosthetic valves and small vegetations."}]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Papillary muscle rupture</strong> classically occurs 2-7 days post-inferior MI (the posteromedial papillary muscle has a single blood supply — the posterior descending artery — versus the dual supply of the anterolateral). A flail leaflet with a wildly eccentric MR jet and abrupt cardiogenic shock is the picture; it is a surgical emergency."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "When TTE quality is limiting or the pretest probability of a structural source is high (prosthetic valve, suspected endocarditis with negative TTE, LAA thrombus assessment before cardioversion), escalate to TEE early rather than serially repeating suboptimal transthoracic studies. Match the modality to the question: TTE for chambers and function, TEE for posterior structures (LA appendage, interatrial septum, mitral apparatus, aortic root, prosthetic valves)."}, {"type": "linkout", "depth": 2, "text": "Labeled examples of McConnell sign, D-shaped septum, valvular vegetations, and papillary muscle rupture are collected on Radiopaedia.", "url": "https://radiopaedia.org/", "label": "Radiopaedia — echocardiography case library"}]}, {"id": "drugs", "title": "Drugs That Change What You See (and Order)", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Echo does not exist in a pharmacologic vacuum. Two drug contexts recur: agents given during the study (stress and contrast) and the guideline-directed therapies whose initiation and titration the echo drives. Know the doses cold — they are asked and they are used."}, {"type": "table", "depth": 1, "label": "Agents used during echocardiography", "head": ["Drug", "Mechanism", "Start dose", "Target/usual dose", "Key contraindication", "Monitoring"], "rows": [["Dobutamine (stress echo)", "β1 agonist → ↑ inotropy/chronotropy", "5-10 mcg/kg/min", "Up to 40 mcg/kg/min ± atropine 0.25-1 mg to reach target HR", "Unstable angina, significant AS (relative), arrhythmia, LVOT obstruction", "Continuous ECG, BP, symptoms, wall-motion at each stage"], ["Dobutamine (low-dose, LFLG AS)", "β1 agonist → ↑ stroke volume", "5 mcg/kg/min", "Up to 20 mcg/kg/min (low-dose protocol)", "Same; watch for hypotension", "Serial AVA, gradient, stroke volume, flow reserve"], ["Agitated saline (\"bubbles\")", "Air microbubbles opacify right heart", "~10 mL agitated saline IV", "Repeat with Valsalva", "Right-to-left shunt with risk of paradoxical air embolism (use minimal air)", "LA appearance timing (≤3 vs >3 beats)"], ["Ultrasound-enhancing agent (contrast)", "Lipid/perflutren microspheres cross pulmonary bed → LV opacification", "Per-label bolus/infusion", "Titrate to LV cavity opacification", "Known hypersensitivity to perflutren; caution with right-to-left shunt", "Watch for rare anaphylactoid reaction"], ["Regadenoson (perfusion stress)", "Coronary vasodilation → flow heterogeneity", "0.4 mg IV bolus", "Single fixed dose", "High-grade AV block, reactive airway (relative), recent caffeine/methylxanthine", "ECG, BP, symptoms; aminophylline reversal available"]]}, {"type": "table", "depth": 2, "label": "GDMT for HFrEF (EF ≤40%) — the four pillars the echo triggers", "head": ["Class / drug", "Mechanism", "Start dose", "Target dose", "Key contraindication", "Side effects / monitoring"], "rows": [["ARNI (sacubitril/valsartan)", "Neprilysin inhibition + ARB → ↑ natriuretic peptides", "24/26 or 49/51 mg BID", "97/103 mg BID", "History of angioedema; 36-h washout from ACEi; pregnancy", "Hypotension, hyperkalemia, renal function; angioedema"], ["Beta-blocker (carvedilol, metoprolol succinate, bisoprolol)", "β-blockade → reverse remodeling", "Carvedilol 3.125 mg BID", "Carvedilol 25 mg BID (50 mg BID if >85 kg)", "Decompensated HF, high-grade block, severe bradycardia", "HR, BP, fatigue; uptitrate q2wk when euvolemic"], ["MRA (spironolactone, eplerenone)", "Aldosterone antagonism", "12.5-25 mg daily", "25-50 mg daily", "K⁺ >5.0, eGFR <30", "Potassium and creatinine at ~3 days, 1 week, then periodically; gynecomastia (spironolactone)"], ["SGLT2 inhibitor (dapagliflozin, empagliflozin)", "Natriuresis / metabolic; benefit across EF", "10 mg daily", "10 mg daily (no titration)", "Type 1 DM, prior DKA; eGFR limits per agent", "Euglycemic DKA, genital mycotic infection, volume status"]]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "<strong>Mnemonic — HFrEF four pillars, \"ABAS\" / quadruple therapy:</strong> <strong>A</strong>RNI (or ACEi/ARB), <strong>B</strong>eta-blocker, <strong>A</strong>ldosterone antagonist (MRA), <strong>S</strong>GLT2 inhibitor. Start all four early and low, then uptitrate — this is the regimen an EF ≤40% on echo should trigger. Landmark trials: PARADIGM-HF (ARNI), DAPA-HF and EMPEROR-Reduced (SGLT2i), RALES and EMPHASIS-HF (MRA)."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "danger", "depth": 2, "text": "Do not start dobutamine stress echo in a patient with severe symptomatic AS, dynamic LVOT obstruction, or recent unstable angina without a specific indication and full monitoring — the inotropic/chronotropic challenge can precipitate ischemia, hypotension, or malignant arrhythmia. Low-dose dobutamine for LFLG AS assessment is a different, controlled protocol."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "The echo increasingly triggers device and structural decisions, not just drugs: EF ≤35% on optimized GDMT for ≥3 months (with the appropriate QRS/etiology criteria) drives ICD/CRT eligibility (informed by DANISH, MADIT-CRT); severe symptomatic AS drives SAVR vs TAVR (PARTNER, Evolut); and severe secondary MR with persistent symptoms on GDMT drives transcatheter edge-to-edge repair candidacy (COAPT). Read the EF as an action item, not a data point."}]}, {"id": "pitfalls", "title": "High-Yield Pitfalls and Artifacts", "body": [{"type": "p", "depth": 1, "text": "Half of echo errors are artifacts mistaken for pathology or angles mistaken for numbers. A short catalog of the classics prevents the most common misreads."}, {"type": "list", "depth": 1, "label": "Common traps", "items": ["<strong>Foreshortening</strong> inflates EF and hides the apex — acquire the longest LV and use contrast for apical thrombus/aneurysm.", "<strong>Off-axis Doppler</strong> underestimates gradients and velocities — align parallel to flow, interrogate from multiple windows in AS and MR.", "<strong>LVOT diameter error</strong> is squared in the continuity equation — the single biggest source of AVA error.", "<strong>Pseudonormal mitral inflow</strong> (Grade II diastolic dysfunction) masquerades as normal — confirm with e′, which does not pseudonormalize, and Valsalva.", "<strong>Reverberation and side-lobe artifacts</strong> mimic thrombus, vegetations, and dissection flaps — confirm any mass in orthogonal planes and question structures that cross anatomic boundaries.", "<strong>Lipomatous atrial septal hypertrophy</strong> spares the fossa (dumbbell shape) and is benign — do not call it a mass.", "<strong>Eustachian valve, Chiari network, and moderator band</strong> are normal RA/RV structures mistaken for pathology.", "<strong>A failing RV with a low TR velocity</strong> looks like mild PH but is severe RV failure — read size and function with pressure."]}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "pearl", "depth": 2, "text": "When a number does not fit the clinical picture, re-measure before you re-diagnose. The most valuable echo skill is skepticism toward your own single measurement — confirm in two views, from two windows, at the correct angle, before you commit a patient to a pathway."}, {"type": "callout", "variant": "fellow", "depth": 3, "text": "Integrate, do not isolate. Guidelines grade valve lesions and diastolic function by a <em>weight of evidence</em> across multiple parameters, not one threshold. A single \"severe\" number surrounded by \"moderate\" supporting data should prompt a search for measurement error or a genuine discordance (e.g., low-flow states) — and often a complementary modality (CT calcium score, cardiac MRI, TEE, or invasive hemodynamics)."}]}], "quiz": [{"stem": "A 72-year-old man with exertional dyspnea has a transthoracic echo. LVEF is 60%. Mitral inflow shows E/A ratio 1.3, average E/e′ 18, LA volume index 42 mL/m², and peak TR velocity 3.1 m/s. Which is the most accurate interpretation of his diastolic function?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Normal diastolic function"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Grade I diastolic dysfunction with normal filling pressures"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Grade II (pseudonormal) diastolic dysfunction with elevated filling pressures"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Indeterminate; the algorithm cannot be applied"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Grade III restrictive physiology"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "With preserved EF, apply the four ASE variables: average E/e′ >14 (18, positive), LAVi >34 (42, positive), TR velocity >2.8 (3.1, positive). Three of four are positive, indicating diastolic dysfunction with elevated filling pressures. His E/A of 1.3 sits in the 0.8-2 pseudonormal window — a mitral inflow that looks deceptively normal while filling pressures are high, consistent with a Grade II pattern. Grade III would require E/A ≥2 with restrictive filling."}, {"stem": "A 58-year-old woman is evaluated for aortic stenosis. Peak jet velocity is 3.2 m/s and mean gradient 28 mmHg, but the calculated aortic valve area is 0.8 cm² and EF is 35%. What is the best next step to determine true severity?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Report moderate AS based on the gradient and stop"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Low-dose dobutamine stress echocardiography"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Immediate surgical aortic valve replacement"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Repeat the study in one year"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Start a beta-blocker to lower the gradient"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is classical low-flow, low-gradient AS: valve area <1.0 cm² (severe by area) but mean gradient <40 mmHg because the reduced EF and low stroke volume cannot generate a high gradient. Low-dose dobutamine stress echo augments flow and distinguishes truly severe AS (area stays <1.0, gradient rises above 40) from pseudo-severe AS (area increases as the weak ventricle opens a pliable valve). It also assesses contractile/flow reserve, which carries prognostic weight. Aortic valve calcium scoring by CT is a complementary adjudicator."}, {"stem": "A 46-year-old man presents with acute pleuritic chest pain and hypoxia. Echo shows a dilated right ventricle, akinesia of the RV mid free wall with a vigorously contracting RV apex, a D-shaped left ventricle in systole, and a TR velocity of 2.9 m/s. Which finding most specifically points to acute pulmonary embolism?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The D-shaped left ventricle"}, {"key": "B", "text": "The TR velocity of 2.9 m/s"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Akinesia of the mid free wall with a spared apex (McConnell sign)"}, {"key": "D", "text": "The dilated right ventricle"}, {"key": "E", "text": "A normal left ventricular ejection fraction"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "McConnell sign — regional akinesia of the RV mid free wall with preserved apical contraction — is relatively specific for acute RV pressure overload from pulmonary embolism, in contrast to the diffuse free-wall hypokinesis of chronic pulmonary hypertension. RV dilation and septal flattening indicate RV strain but are nonspecific. The modestly elevated TR velocity reflects the acutely overloaded thin RV's inability to generate high pressure (part of the 60/60 sign), and a normal LVEF is expected and nonspecific."}, {"stem": "A 60-year-old woman with progressive edema and dyspnea has echo showing a septal bounce, preserved medial mitral annular e′ of 9 cm/s that exceeds the lateral e′, >30% respirophasic variation in mitral E velocity, and expiratory diastolic flow reversal in the hepatic veins. Which diagnosis do these findings support?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Restrictive cardiomyopathy"}, {"key": "B", "text": "Constrictive pericarditis"}, {"key": "C", "text": "Cardiac tamponade"}, {"key": "D", "text": "Severe mitral stenosis"}, {"key": "E", "text": "Acute pulmonary embolism"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "This is the classic constellation of constrictive pericarditis: a septal bounce from enhanced ventricular interdependence, marked respirophasic mitral inflow variation (>25%), expiratory hepatic-vein diastolic reversal, and — the fellowship pearls — annulus paradoxus (preserved/high medial e′ despite high filling pressure) and annulus reversus (medial e′ > lateral e′, the reverse of normal). Restrictive cardiomyopathy shows reduced e′, minimal respiratory variation, and inspiratory hepatic-vein reversal. Distinguishing the two is decisive because constriction is surgically curable by pericardiectomy."}, {"stem": "During a routine echo, the sonographer performs an agitated saline study. The right atrium opacifies fully, and bubbles appear in the left atrium after 6 cardiac cycles. What does this most likely indicate?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "A patent foramen ovale"}, {"key": "B", "text": "A secundum atrial septal defect"}, {"key": "C", "text": "An intrapulmonary shunt such as a pulmonary arteriovenous malformation"}, {"key": "D", "text": "A ventricular septal defect"}, {"key": "E", "text": "A normal study with no shunt"}], "correct": "C", "explanation": "Timing separates the shunt. Bubbles crossing to the left atrium within about 3 beats indicate an intracardiac shunt (PFO or ASD). Delayed appearance after 3-5 or more cycles — here 6 beats — indicates an intrapulmonary shunt, because the microbubbles traverse the pulmonary circulation before reaching the left heart. This pattern is seen with pulmonary AVMs and hepatopulmonary syndrome. A VSD would not be detected by this atrial-level test in this fashion, and the study is clearly abnormal."}, {"stem": "A 68-year-old man has severe primary mitral regurgitation being quantified by the PISA method. The color Nyquist baseline is shifted to an aliasing velocity of 40 cm/s, the PISA radius is 1.0 cm, and the peak MR jet velocity is 500 cm/s. Which calculated value indicates severe MR, and what is the effective regurgitant orifice area?", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "EROA 0.10 cm² — mild"}, {"key": "B", "text": "EROA 0.50 cm² — severe"}, {"key": "C", "text": "EROA 0.25 cm² — moderate"}, {"key": "D", "text": "EROA 0.05 cm² — trivial"}, {"key": "E", "text": "EROA cannot be calculated from these data"}], "correct": "B", "explanation": "PISA flow rate = 2πr² × aliasing velocity = 2 × 3.14 × (1.0 cm)² × 40 cm/s ≈ 251 cm³/s. EROA = flow rate ÷ peak MR velocity = 251 ÷ 500 ≈ 0.50 cm². An EROA ≥0.40 cm² meets the threshold for severe primary MR. This method assumes a single hemispheric circular orifice; eccentric or multiple jets and non-circular orifices (common in secondary MR) undermine it, so PISA should be integrated with vena contracta width and pulmonary vein flow reversal."}], "takeaways": ["Read every study in the same fixed order (Images, LV, Diastole, RV, LA/RA, Valves, Pericardium, Aorta/IVC, Septa) and confirm every abnormal finding in two views before believing it.", "Report EF by biplane Simpson (or 3D/contrast when windows are poor), never by Teichholz in regional disease, and add GLS — apical sparing (\"cherry on top\") is the amyloid signature and reduced GLS with preserved EF is the earliest cardiotoxicity signal.", "Diastolic function needs the full four-variable ASE algorithm (LAVi >34, average E/e′ >14, TR velocity >2.8, septal e′ <7 / lateral e′ <10), and pseudonormal Grade II inflow is a red flag, not reassurance.", "Assess the RV with a panel — TAPSE <17 mm, S′ <9.5 cm/s, FAC <35% — and remember a failing RV can generate a deceptively low TR velocity; McConnell sign points to acute PE.", "Use the right quantification method per lesion: continuity equation for AS (LVOT diameter is the squared error trap; beware low-gradient severe AS), PISA/vena contracta for regurgitation, and pressure half-time (MVA = 220/PHT) for mitral stenosis.", "Tamponade is a hemodynamic diagnosis (RA systolic and RV diastolic collapse, >30% respirophasic mitral inflow drop, IVC plethora) — and annulus paradoxus/reversus plus a septal bounce separate operable constriction from restriction.", "Read the EF and valve severity as action items: EF ≤40% triggers the four GDMT pillars (ARNI/ACEi, beta-blocker, MRA, SGLT2i), and severe lesions trigger structural decisions (TAVR, TEER, pericardiectomy)."], "references": ["Mitchell C, et al. Guidelines for Performing a Comprehensive Transthoracic Echocardiographic Examination in Adults: Recommendations from the American Society of Echocardiography. J Am Soc Echocardiogr, 2019", "Lang RM, et al. Recommendations for Cardiac Chamber Quantification by Echocardiography in Adults: An Update from the ASE and EACVI. J Am Soc Echocardiogr, 2015", "Nagueh SF, et al. Recommendations for the Evaluation of Left Ventricular Diastolic Function by Echocardiography: An Update from the ASE and EACVI. J Am Soc Echocardiogr, 2016", "Rudski LG, et al. Guidelines for the Echocardiographic Assessment of the Right Heart in Adults: A Report from the American Society of Echocardiography. J Am Soc Echocardiogr, 2010", "Baumgartner H, et al. Recommendations on the Echocardiographic Assessment of Aortic Valve Stenosis: A Focused Update from the EACVI and ASE. J Am Soc Echocardiogr / Eur Heart J Cardiovasc Imaging, 2017", "Zoghbi WA, et al. Recommendations for Noninvasive Evaluation of Native Valvular Regurgitation: A Report from the American Society of Echocardiography. J Am Soc Echocardiogr, 2017", "Otto CM, Nishimura RA, et al. 2020 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Valvular Heart Disease. Circulation / J Am Coll Cardiol, 2021", "Heidenreich PA, et al. 2022 AHA/ACC/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure. Circulation, 2022"]};
